00:09:26  INFO      causal_agent.research_planner  |  tool call >> save_file({'filename': 'manifest_attempt_1.md', 'content': '# Mun Orbit Mission Rocket Manifest — Attempt 1\n\n## Mission target\nLaunch from Kerbin and achieve a stable Mun orbit with periapsis >= 10 km and apoapsis <= 500 km.\n\n## Sources used\n- KSP Wiki search/box snippets confirming exact stock part names and key stats:\n  - `LV-T45 "Swivel" Liquid Fuel Engine` — 200 kN thrust, 250 s sea-level Isp, 320 s vacuum Isp, 1.5 t mass\n  - `LV-909 "Terrier" Liquid Fuel Engine` — 60 kN thrust, 85 s sea-level Isp, 345 s vacuum Isp, 0.5 t mass\n  - `FL-T800 Fuel Tank` — 4.5 t full mass, 0.5 t dry mass\n  - `FL-T400 Fuel Tank` — 2.25 t full mass, 0.25 t dry mass\n  - `FL-T100 Fuel Tank` — 0.5625 t full mass, 0.0625 t dry mass\n  - `TD-12 Decoupler`\n  - `Advanced Inline Stabilizer`\n  - `Probodobodyne OKTO2`\n- KSP community delta-v map / cheat-sheet values indicating approximately 4550 m/s to stable Kerbin orbit, about 860 m/s for Mun transfer, and about 210–310 m/s for Mun capture. Required mission total with margin: >= 5250 m/s.\n\n## Design summary\nThis is a simple two-stage inline stock liquid rocket. The first stage handles launch and atmospheric ascent with a gimballed `LV-T45 "Swivel" Liquid Fuel Engine`. The second stage uses a `LV-909 "Terrier" Liquid Fuel Engine` for vacuum-efficient circularization, Trans-Mun Injection, and Mun Orbit Insertion. Attitude control is provided by the probe core, `Advanced Inline Stabilizer`, and Swivel gimbal. RCS is intentionally omitted to avoid unnecessary dry mass.\n\n## Exact part list (top to bottom)\n1. `Probodobodyne OKTO2`\n2. `Advanced Inline Stabilizer`\n3. `FL-T100 Fuel Tank`\n4. `FL-T400 Fuel Tank`\n5. `LV-909 "Terrier" Liquid Fuel Engine`\n6. `TD-12 Decoupler`\n7. `FL-T800 Fuel Tank`\n8. `FL-T800 Fuel Tank`\n9. `FL-T400 Fuel Tank`\n10. `LV-T45 "Swivel" Liquid Fuel Engine`\n11. Launch clamps as needed for pad stability\n\n## Stage table\n| Stage | Purpose | Exact active parts | Decoupler placement | Ignition mass (t) | Burnout mass before separation (t) | Isp used | Delta-v (m/s) | TWR at ignition |\n|---|---|---|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| 1 | Launch, gravity turn, set Kerbin apoapsis to 80–100 km | `LV-T45 "Swivel" Liquid Fuel Engine` + `FL-T800 Fuel Tank` + `FL-T800 Fuel Tank` + `FL-T400 Fuel Tank` | `TD-12 Decoupler` directly above the first-stage tanks, between the Swivel booster stack and the Terrier upper stage | 14.80 | 3.55 | 285 s effective ascent average | 3960 | 1.38 at Kerbin sea level |\n| 2 | Circularization, TMI, MOI, correction margin | `LV-909 "Terrier" Liquid Fuel Engine` + `FL-T400 Fuel Tank` + `FL-T100 Fuel Tank` + `Advanced Inline Stabilizer` + `Probodobodyne OKTO2` | No further decoupler; terminal stage | 3.50 | 0.80 | 345 s vacuum | 5090 | 1.75 in vacuum |\n\n## Total performance\n- Total delta-v: **9050 m/s**\n- Required minimum: **5250 m/s**\n- Margin over requirement: **3800 m/s**\n\n## Calculation notes\n### Stage 2\nUsing:\n- wet mass = 3.50 t\n- dry mass = 0.80 t\n- Isp = 345 s\n\nDelta-v:\n- dV = 345 × 9.81 × ln(3.50 / 0.80) ≈ **5090 m/s**\n\nUpper-stage TWR:\n- TWR = 60,000 / (3,500 × 9.81) ≈ **1.75**\n\n### Stage 1\nUsing:\n- full launch mass = 14.80 t\n- mass at first-stage burnout before separation = 3.55 t\n- effective ascent Isp = 285 s to represent mixed sea-level / upper-atmosphere operation\n\nDelta-v:\n- dV = 285 × 9.81 × ln(14.80 / 3.55) ≈ **3960 m/s**\n\nFirst-stage launch TWR:\n- TWR = 200,000 / (14,800 × 9.81) ≈ **1.38**\n\n## SAS / RCS specification\n- SAS / torque sources:\n  - `Probodobodyne OKTO2` on the top of the stack\n  - `Advanced Inline Stabilizer` directly below the probe core on the upper stage\n  - engine gimbal on the `LV-T45 "Swivel" Liquid Fuel Engine` during ascent\n- RCS: **Not installed**\n\n## Decoupler and staging plan\n- `TD-12 Decoupler` is placed between the upper-stage Terrier stack and the lower-stage Swivel booster stack.\n- Recommended staging order in the VAB:\n  1. First activation: ignite `LV-T45 "Swivel" Liquid Fuel Engine`\n  2. Second activation: decouple the empty first stage via `TD-12 Decoupler`\n  3. Third activation: ignite `LV-909 "Terrier" Liquid Fuel Engine`\n\n## Build notes for operator\n- Build exactly as a straight inline stack in the listed top-to-bottom order.\n- Do not add boosters, fins, fairings, or extra tanks beyond this manifest.\n- Place sufficient launch clamps for pad stability.\n- Ensure the Terrier is mounted directly below the upper-stage tanks and directly above the `TD-12 Decoupler`.\n- Ensure the Swivel is mounted directly below the lower-stage tanks.\n\n## Mission rationale\n- The first stage satisfies the required launch TWR >= 1.3.\n- The upper stage has enough vacuum TWR for circularization and capture burns.\n- Total delta-v greatly exceeds the >= 5250 m/s requirement, so the design is robust against gravity losses and modest piloting inefficiency.\n- The design uses only simple, common stock parts with exact KSP names.\n\n## Uncertainty note\nThe live KSP Wiki pages are protected by anti-bot tooling, but accessible wiki snippets and mirrored stock-part references consistently confirm the exact part names and core stats used above. The large delta-v margin means small residual stat uncertainty would not materially change mission viability.'})
