02:30:35  INFO      causal_agent.research_planner  |  tool call >> save_file({'filename': 'manifest_attempt_6.md', 'content': '# Mun Orbit Mission Manifest — Attempt 6\n\n## Failure analysis from Attempt 5\n**Failure mode:** Uncommanded late burn / guidance oscillation while already in stable Kerbin parking orbit.\n\n**Operator report:** the vehicle was orbiting Kerbin stably, then after the 4th orbit the script "randomly decid[ed] to burn your remaining fuel" while guidance shook the craft back and forth.\n\n**Specific telemetry evidence from `telemetry.txt`:**\n- Parking orbit was not actually achieved at circularization; periapsis remained too low during the long coast: for example,\n  - `[T+230s] AP=90882m | PE=46535m | BODY=Kerbin | PHASE=COAST_TO_AP`\n  - `[T+271s] AP=6529142m | PE=48977m | BODY=Kerbin | PHASE=COAST_TO_AP`\n  - `[T+563s] AP=348213m | PE=49011m | BODY=Kerbin | PHASE=COAST_TO_AP`\n- That means the upper stage was still thrusting or still being interpreted as in an active burn state after ascent cutoff, inflating apoapsis from the intended ~90 km to millions of meters.\n\n**Root cause:**\n1. The ascent / stage transition logic was not reliably detecting engine cutoff and stage separation, so the second stage continued accelerating during what should have been the coast to apoapsis.\n2. The guidance logic then remained alive for multiple orbits and later re-entered burn logic, causing the observed fuel dump and attitude oscillation.\n3. Telemetry used `flight().speed` in a default frame that did not reflect useful ascent diagnostics, so the log was less trustworthy than it should have been.\n\n## Design revision for Attempt 6\nKeep the **same proven rocket family** but simplify the automation assumptions:\n- Strong first stage for ascent.\n- Large, efficient upper stage for circularization, TMI, and MOI.\n- Script revision will add:\n  - explicit stage fuel depletion checks,\n  - bounded waits so it never idles for multiple orbits,\n  - no indefinite prograde holding after parking orbit,\n  - node-based TMI search with hard stop criteria,\n  - corrected telemetry frame.\n\n---\n\n## Exact parts list\nBuild exactly in this top-to-bottom stack order:\n\n1. **Mk1 Command Pod**\n2. **Mk16 Parachute**\n3. **Advanced Inline Stabilizer**\n4. **Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank**\n5. **Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank**\n6. **RE-L10 "Poodle" Liquid Fuel Engine**\n7. **TD-25 Decoupler**\n8. **Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank**\n9. **Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank**\n10. **RE-M3 "Mainsail" Liquid Engine**\n11. **4 x AV-T1 Winglet** on the bottom stage\n12. **4 x EAS-4 Strut Connector** reinforcing lower tank stack / upper stage interface as needed\n13. **3 x TT18-A Launch Stability Enhancer**\n\nNo boosters, no fairings, no RCS blocks.\n\n---\n\n## SAS / RCS specification\n- **SAS / reaction control source:**\n  - **Mk1 Command Pod** built-in reaction wheel\n  - **Advanced Inline Stabilizer** on the upper stage\n- **RCS thrusters:** none\n- **Monopropellant:** none required\n\nThis is sufficient because the Poodle stage has low gimbal needs and the reaction wheel stack is adequate for TMI/MOI pointing.\n\n---\n\n## Decoupler placement\n- Place **TD-25 Decoupler** directly between:\n  - the **upper stage** (`RE-L10 "Poodle"` + `2 x Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank` + pod stack), and\n  - the **lower stage** (`RE-M3 "Mainsail"` + `2 x Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank`).\n\n---\n\n## Stage table (order of firing)\n\n| Firing order | Purpose | Engine(s) | Propellant tanks | Decoupler event | Estimated ΔV | Estimated TWR at ignition |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---:|---:|\n| 1 | Launch, gravity turn, majority of ascent | **RE-M3 "Mainsail" Liquid Engine** | **2 x Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank** | After depletion, fire **TD-25 Decoupler** and ignite stage 2 | ~2,900 m/s | ~1.85 at Kerbin sea level |\n| 2 | Finish ascent, circularization, TMI, MOI, reserve | **RE-L10 "Poodle" Liquid Fuel Engine** | **2 x Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank** | none | ~3,150 m/s | ~0.95 in vacuum at ignition, rising as propellant drains |\n\n**Total planned ΔV:** **~6,050 m/s**\n\nThis exceeds the required **5,250 m/s** mission minimum by a comfortable margin.\n\n---\n\n## Staging order to set in VAB\nUse this exact staging logic:\n\n### Stage 0 (first action at launch)\n- **TT18-A Launch Stability Enhancer** release\n- **RE-M3 "Mainsail" Liquid Engine** ignition\n\n### Stage 1\n- **TD-25 Decoupler**\n- **RE-L10 "Poodle" Liquid Fuel Engine** ignition\n\n### Stage 2\n- **Mk16 Parachute** (unused during mission, but leave armed only for recovery after manual post-mission return if desired)\n\nDo **not** place the parachute in any stage that could fire during ascent.\n\n---\n\n## Why this vehicle is still appropriate\n- The operator reported the prior vehicle could already reach and maintain Kerbin orbit.\n- The failure signature points to **automation logic**, not to inadequate thrust or delta-v.\n- This stack has:\n  - strong launch TWR,\n  - enough upper-stage delta-v for Mun transfer and capture,\n  - simple two-stage sequencing that is easy to detect in kRPC.\n\n---\n\n## Part/stat grounding\nExact part names above are stock-valid KSP 1.x names. Numeric planning is grounded in standard stock stats cross-checked against KSP wiki mirrors / community tables:\n- `Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank`\n- `Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank`\n- `RE-M3 "Mainsail" Liquid Engine`\n- `RE-L10 "Poodle" Liquid Fuel Engine`\n- `TD-25 Decoupler`\n- `Advanced Inline Stabilizer`\n- `AV-T1 Winglet`\n- `TT18-A Launch Stability Enhancer`\n\nOfficial wiki pages were partially anti-bot protected during this run, so the part names are exact and the performance numbers are conservative planning estimates based on stock KSP 1.x values.\n\n---\n\n## Operator build notes\n- Fuel tanks are inline only; no asparagus, no crossfeed tricks.\n- Put the 4 winglets symmetrically on the lower stage near the Mainsail.\n- Use struts if needed to suppress wobble.\n- Launch from the pad with kRPC connected before running the script.\n- No manual inputs after the script starts.'})
