03:30:31  INFO      causal_agent.research_planner  |  tool call >> save_file({'filename': 'manifest_attempt_10.md', 'content': '# Mun Orbit Mission Manifest — Attempt 10\n\n## Failure analysis from Attempt 9\n**Failure mode:** Vehicle destruction by atmospheric re-entry while still waiting in Kerbin orbit for the TMI window.\n\n**Operator telemetry:**\n- `[T+1944s] ALT=90461m | SURF_ALT=90461m | SPD=0.0m/s | AP=95578m | PE=89506m | BODY=Kerbin | FUEL=54.7% | PHASE=WAIT_TMI_WINDOW`\n- Then: **“Rocket exploded in the upper atmosphere.”**\n\n## Specific diagnosis\nThe telemetry shows the script loitered in Kerbin orbit for an extended period before TMI. That created a long unattended wait, and the vehicle was later destroyed before transfer. Given the reported altitude and phase, the most likely software issue is:\n1. the phase-angle waiting logic stalled or behaved incorrectly,\n2. the script remained in `WAIT_TMI_WINDOW` instead of committing to a transfer,\n3. the mission then failed before any Mun burn began.\n\n## Root cause\n**TMI window waiting logic was too fragile and overcomplicated.**\n\nAt this point, a more robust strategy is to stop trying to perfectly wait for a theoretical transfer window and instead:\n- reach LKO,\n- immediately create a high-energy TMI node near the next prograde opportunity,\n- numerically search around burn time and delta-v,\n- execute the best candidate,\n- then do MOI on arrival.\n\nThis avoids indefinite waiting in orbit.\n\n## Design choice for Attempt 10\nKeep the same strong three-stage vehicle from Attempts 8 and 9, because the physical rocket was capable enough; the new fix is entirely script logic.\n\n---\n\n## Exact parts list\nBuild exactly in this top-to-bottom stack order:\n\n1. **Mk1 Command Pod**\n2. **Mk16 Parachute**\n3. **Advanced Inline Stabilizer**\n4. **FL-T400 Fuel Tank**\n5. **FL-T400 Fuel Tank**\n6. **LV-909 "Terrier" Liquid Fuel Engine**\n7. **TD-12 Decoupler**\n8. **Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank**\n9. **Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank**\n10. **RE-L10 "Poodle" Liquid Fuel Engine**\n11. **TD-25 Decoupler**\n12. **Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank**\n13. **Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank**\n14. **RE-M3 "Mainsail" Liquid Engine**\n15. **4 x AV-T1 Winglet** on lower stage\n16. **6 x EAS-4 Strut Connector** reinforcing stack as needed\n17. **3 x TT18-A Launch Stability Enhancer**\n\n---\n\n## SAS / RCS specification\n- **SAS / reaction control:**\n  - **Mk1 Command Pod** reaction wheel\n  - **Advanced Inline Stabilizer**\n- **RCS:** none\n- **Monopropellant:** none\n\n---\n\n## Decoupler placement\n- **TD-12 Decoupler** between Terrier final stage and Poodle transfer stage.\n- **TD-25 Decoupler** between Poodle transfer stage and Mainsail launch stage.\n\n---\n\n## Stage table (order of firing)\n\n| Firing order | Purpose | Engine(s) | Propellant tanks | Decoupler placement | Estimated ΔV | Estimated TWR at ignition |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---:|---:|\n| 1 | Launch, gravity turn, bulk ascent | **RE-M3 "Mainsail" Liquid Engine** | **2 x Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank** | **TD-25** above stage 1 | ~2,700 m/s | ~1.70–1.85 at Kerbin sea level |\n| 2 | Circularization and most of TMI | **RE-L10 "Poodle" Liquid Fuel Engine** | **2 x Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank** | **TD-12** above stage 2 | ~2,000 m/s | ~0.75–0.90 in vacuum |\n| 3 | Mun capture and reserve | **LV-909 "Terrier" Liquid Fuel Engine** | **2 x FL-T400 Fuel Tank** | none | ~1,900 m/s | ~0.45 in vacuum |\n\n**Total planned ΔV:** **~6,600 m/s**\n\nThis remains above the required **5,250 m/s** threshold.\n\n---\n\n## VAB staging order\nSet staging exactly as follows:\n\n### Stage 0\n- **TT18-A Launch Stability Enhancer** release\n- **RE-M3 "Mainsail" Liquid Engine** ignition\n\n### Stage 1\n- **TD-25 Decoupler**\n- **RE-L10 "Poodle" Liquid Fuel Engine** ignition\n\n### Stage 2\n- **TD-12 Decoupler**\n- **LV-909 "Terrier" Liquid Fuel Engine** ignition\n\n### Stage 3\n- **Mk16 Parachute** only\n\n---\n\n## Operator notes\n- Same rocket as the previous attempt.\n- This attempt removes the fragile long wait for a transfer window.\n- No manual intervention during flight.\n- kRPC connected before running the script.\n\n---\n\n## Grounding note\nExact part names are stock-valid KSP 1.x names. Performance numbers are planning estimates based on accessible stock references and community mirrors.'})
