15:30:13  INFO      causal_agent.research_planner  |  tool call >> save_file({'filename': 'hypotheses_1.md', 'content': '# Hypotheses for Attempt 1\n\n## Current belief state\n\nThis is the first attempt. No prior evidence exists. I believe a well-designed 3-stage rocket with sufficient dV margin and a properly instrumented kRPC script can achieve a stable Mun orbit.\n\n## Material uncertainties\n\n### U1: Rocket design — is the dV budget sufficient?\nThe canonical budget is ~4,570 m/s (3,400 LKO + 860 TMI + 310 MOI). With 15% margin: ~5,250 m/s.\n\n**H1a:** A 3-stage rocket with LV-T30 (stage 1), LV-T45 (stage 2), and LV-909 Terrier (stage 3) provides ≥ 5,250 m/s vacuum dV.\n**H1b:** The dV is insufficient (< 5,250 m/s), requiring more fuel or a different engine configuration.\n\n### U2: Gravity turn profile — will the ascent reach 80-100 km apoapsis?\n**H2a:** A linear pitch transition from 90° at launch to ~0° by 45 km, with throttle-back at high Q, will reach AP ≥ 80 km before leaving the atmosphere.\n**H2b:** The turn is too aggressive, causing the rocket to lose too much vertical velocity and fail to reach target AP.\n**H2c:** The turn is too shallow, causing the rocket to exit the atmosphere before gaining enough horizontal velocity, requiring excessive circularization dV.\n\n### U3: Circularization — can we achieve stable LKO?\n**H3a:** A prograde burn at apoapsis with the Terrier engine can circularize to PE ≥ 75 km.\n**H3b:** The Terrier\'s low thrust (60 kN) may not circularize in time before the next apoapsis pass.\n\n### U4: TMI timing — can we get a Mun encounter?\n**H4a:** A Hohmann transfer computed analytically (dV ≈ 860 m/s) placed at the next apoapsis will produce a Mun encounter.\n**H4b:** The phase angle will be wrong and the Mun encounter will not occur without a correction burn.\n\n### U5: MOI — can we capture into Mun orbit?\n**H5a:** A retrograde burn at Mun periapsis with the Terrier can capture into a stable orbit (PE ≥ 10 km, AP ≤ 500 km).\n**H5b:** Insufficient fuel remains after TMI for the MOI burn.\n\n## Predictions\n\nIf H1a is correct:\n- The rocket\'s total vacuum dV (calculated via Tsiolkovsky) will be ≥ 5,250 m/s.\n- Fuel remaining after LKO insertion will be > 40%.\n- Fuel remaining after TMI will be > 15%.\n\nIf H2a is correct:\n- AP will reach 80-100 km between MET ~120-180s.\n- Maximum Q will be < 25,000 Pa.\n- The rocket will still be below 70 km altitude when AP target is reached.\n\nIf H3a is correct:\n- After circularization burn, PE ≥ 75,000 m and AP ≈ 80,000-100,000 m.\n- Circularization dV will be in the range 100-300 m/s.\n\nIf H4a is correct:\n- After TMI burn, vessel.orbit.next_orbit.body.name == \'Mun\'.\n- TMI dV ≈ 840-900 m/s.\n- Time to Mun SOI will be < 12 hours.\n\nIf H5a is correct:\n- After MOI burn, BODY = Mun, PE ≥ 10,000 m, AP ≤ 500,000 m.\n- Fuel remaining > 5%.\n\n## Experiment design\n\nAttempt 1 is a baseline. The rocket is designed conservatively with:\n- Stage 1: 1x LV-T30 "Reliant" + 2x FL-T800 tanks (high TWR for launch)\n- Stage 2: 1x LV-T45 "Swivel" + 1x FL-T800 tank (gimbaling for ascent control)\n- Stage 3: 1x LV-909 "Terrier" + 1x FL-T400 tank (vacuum-optimized for transfer/insertion)\n- Mk1 Command Pod + Mk16 Parachute + TR-18A decouplers\n\nThe script will implement the full mission profile with self-instrumentation.\n'})
